ted Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Sturmy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Sturmey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Sturmey","meanings":["English: (i) nickname from Middle English  <i>stormi</i> ‘stormy’ (Old French  <i>estormi</i>), for someone with a stormy temperament.  Compare  Storm   relationship name from the Middle English personal name  <i>Sturmi</i>,  <i>Sturmy</i> (Old French * <i>Estourmi</i>, Continental Germanic  <i>Sturmi</i>)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":26,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William de Sturmy was born in 1356, in Hall End, Warwickshire, England as the son of Geoffrey De Sturmy and Mrs Geoffrey de Sturmy. He married Joan Stockhay before 1374. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. In 1418, at the age of 62, his occupation is listed as high sheriff of wiltshire. He died on 21 March 1427, in Elvetham, Hampshire, England, at the age of 71, and was buried in Easton near Devizes, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1356–21 March 1427":"1356–21. märts 1427","1356–1427":"1356–1427","1339–1429":"1339–1429","1374–1420":"1374–1420","–Female":"Surnud","1325–1381":"1325–1381","October 1388":"oktoober 1388","1374":"1374","1382":"1382","1381":"1381","1404":"1404","21 March 1427":"21. märts 1427","1325":"1325","1356":"1356","BEF 1374":"enne 1374","Abt 1420":"umbes 1420","1420":"1420","1418":"1418","1429":"1429","1427":"1427","1339":"1339","Wolf Hall, Wiltshire, England":"Wolf Hall, Wiltshire, England","Hall End, Warwickshire, England":"Hall End, Warwickshire, England","Elvetham, Hampshire, England":"Elvetham, Hampshire, England","Easton Priory, Easton, Wiltshire, England":"Easton near Devizes, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1356–21 March 1427":"1356–21. maaliskuuta 1427","1356–1427":"1356–1427","1339–1429":"1339–1429","1374–1420":"1374–1420","–Female":"Kuollut","1325–1381":"1325–1381","October 1388":"lokakuu 1388","1374":"1374","1382":"1382","1381":"1381","1404":"1404","21 March 1427":"21. maaliskuuta 1427","1